@node Introduction "Introduction"
@{fg shine}
            LanguageGUI V3.00 - By: John White - PUBLIC DOMAIN.
           -----------------------------------------------------
@{fg text}
 LanguageGUI (LGUI) is a Graphical User Interface for `Speaking' Languages
 such as GERMAN, FRENCH, ITALIAN, SPANISH, TAGALOG (Philippines), etc. It
 has, hopefully, been designed to make your life a little bit easier when
 learning a `Speaking' language.

 LGUI needs at least Operating System 39 and ¾ to 2Mb to work.

@{fg shine}
 General Information@{fg text}

 * About 99% of Memory is allocated only when it is needed and deleted
   as soon as it is no longer needed. Fast Ram will be used where possible.
@{fg fill}
 The Speech Memory will only be set-up if the Speech File is Loaded. If an
 error occurs whilst loading the file (I.e it is not of the correct Format)
 LGUI will delete the speech memory. Thus, no memory wastage.@{fg text}

 * LGUI (including the LGUI disk contents) is about 99% finished - LGUI may
   need little things doing to it.

 * Most functions can use a Keyboard Key, aswell Mouse_Key/s, and are high-
   lighted with a White character. Here is a list of those keyboard keys
   NOT highlighted with a White character....

      Main Screen:   Left-Shift and ESC  =  Quit LGUI.

                   NumerPad Up and Down  =  Move up/down (display) one item.


   Options Screen:    F1 to F10 and DEL  =  Hightlight the left categories.

                      F1 to F10 and DEL  =  Hightlight the right categories.
                      (with Left-Shift)

                     Left-Shift and ESC  =  Quit LGUI.

 * A1200 owners, etc should use a PAL-HIRES ScreenMode as opposed to one of
   the AGA Multiscan ScreenModes (DblPal, etc).

 * Advanced Amiga Basic (by Compute! books) is worth reading as it has a few
   pages covering Amiga Phonetic Speech - pages 168 to 171 if I remember.

 * LGUI was released to give you a G.U.I for your Speaking Languages. Please
   do not think it should have Languages released with it because it does
   not. TAGALOG was supplied purely as an example as to how you should
   construct your language files for LGUI use.

   The aim of the language files is that once you have decided to learn a
   language, wether that is because you are going on Holiday or because you
   are a Student of some sort or whatever, you make your language files to
   contain only those Words/Sentences that you will be needing and/or
   learning. For example. Your holiday language files might only contain
   common words and sentences, to get you by whilst on holiday. Whereas
   your student language files might contain 1000+ words and sentences, as
   you are trying to learn that language.
@{fg shine}
 Warning@{fg text}

 Because I do not know everything about the Amiga and its Speech, I will not
