@node Why "So Why Learn A Language?"
@{fg shine}
 LIKE ANY LANGUAGE, YOU HAVE TO LOOK AT WHAT YOU MAY GAIN FROM LEARNING IT.
@{fg text}
 *  The ability to speak to Foreign people. Thus, make New Friends, be
    invited to (even more) Parties!, Chat-Up the opposite/same sex
    (We are in the year 2001!), etc.

 *  The ability to speak the language of the country you are visiting.

 *  The ability to get a Job in a foreign country.

 *  Be able to talk about something in a foreign language without your
    own speaking language people knowing what you are talking about.
@{fg shine}
 SOME REASONS FOR WANTING/NEEDING TO LEARN A FOREIGN LANGUAGE.
@{fg text}
 *  So that you can enjoy yourself on holiday with the Local people.

 *  So that you can talk to Hotel Staff (If there is a problem with your
    Hotel Room, etc) or an Emergency Crew (If you end up in Hospital, etc)
    whilst on Holiday.

 *  Perhaps your New Partner does not speak your own language that well?
    If so. Instead of leaving your partner to learn your language you could
    always learn each others language. Learning can be Fun. Especially when
    it comes to learning what each Body Part is called!!

 *  Job Opportunities.
@{fg shine}
 TWO GOOD REASONS/ADVANTAGES FOR LEARNING A FOREIGN LANGUAGE ARE:
@{fg text}
 1) Most people are surprised you can talk their language and thus tend to
    show more interest in you.

 2) You are showing people you are willing to Learn, Communicate, Make An
    Effort, etc.

 @{" One Method Of Learning " Link "Method"}
@endnode

@node Method "One Method Of Learning"

 1) Try and learn the Basic Words first. Like @{fg shine}Why@{fg text},@{fg shine} Who@{fg text},@{fg shine} What@{fg text},@{fg shine} Where@{fg text},@{fg shine} You@{fg text},
    @{fg shine}I@{fg text},@{fg shine} Me@{fg text},@{fg shine} Her@{fg text} and so on.

 2) Listen to your foreign friends when they speak to each other - Try and
    see if you can identify any of the words you have learnt. You should
    begin to reckonize, by the tone of voices and body-language, whether or
    not someone is Asking a question (Why, What, etc), Talking about someone
    (He, They, etc) or whatever. By doing this early on you should gain some
    Hearing as to expressing yourself (Tone of voice, Loudness, etc).

 3) Once you have learnt about 100 Basic Words (or about 150 Assorted Words)
    learn some Basic Sentences, Comments, etc. Like @{fg shine}Hello@{fg text},@{fg shine} Good Afternoon@{fg text},
    @{fg shine}How Are You@{fg text},@{fg shine} The Weather Is Bad@{fg text}, etc.
@{fg fill}
    Learn the Words first. If you learn the Sentences first you will be
    flickering through a Dictionary, most of the time, looking up word
    meanings. This may seem an obvious point but it is an easy point to
    forget when you are eager to learn a language via its sentences first.@{fg text}

 4) At this stage keep your words and sentences simple, as above. Keep
    repeating steps 1-3 until you can comfortably remember about 50 words
    and about 20 short sentences - The reason I say this is because if you
    learn too many words/sentences at this stage you may forget some of them
    later. Especially if they are words/sentences that look useful at the
    time but are not used in every-day speech. This is why it is vital to
    carefully select your words and sentences.

 5) Try and join a few words together, to make small sentences, using the
    in-between words. [He]@{fg shine} Is A @{fg text}[Teacher], [She]@{fg shine} Is On The @{fg text}[Telephone],
    [They]@{fg shine} Are In The @{fg text}[Kitchen], etc. [] means the word is optional. By
    learning some of the in-between words early on you can begin to form
    your own small sentences, by simply replacing the optional words - If
    the language permits this.

 6) Keep repeating step 5 until you comfortably know quite a few short
    sentences - Even if those short sentences are only things like
    [I] Am A [Teacher], [She] Is A [Nurse], [TOM] Is In The [Garden],
    [The Food] Is On The [Table], It Is [Raining], etc.

 7) Now try and learn a few more short words and sentences.

 8) Now you know quite a few bits and pieces, try and learn Commands and
    Questions, etc. Like @{fg shine}[Where] is [TOM]?@{fg text},@{fg shine} [Wash] Your [Hands]@{fg text},@{fg shine} Wait There@{fg text},
    @{fg shine}[How Much] Is [This]?@{fg text}, @{fg shine}[Open] The [Window]@{fg text}, etc - They are Very Short,
    but effective.

 9) Keep repeating step 8, building up your sentences. You should find after
    a while, especially if you have been speaking (aswell as remembering)
    the above type of sentences, that things start to fall into place and
    you can remember sentences and words with a lot more ease, etc.

10) Now it is time to learn the Categories. Learn each category, slowly as
    above, until you can correctly remember and say about 95% of a category.
    You do not need to learn one category at a time. You could learn the
    same two categories each day, learning about 25% of each category, and
    then learn two different categories a week later for example. Thus,
    learning a bit of each category over a period of a few weeks/months.
@{fg fill}
    The above sentences, etc are only examples. The above method is loosely
    based on the way I started to learn TAGALOG.@{fg text}

 @{" Tips " Link "Tips"}
@endnode

@node Tips "Tips"

 * Try and be around a friend who speaks the language you are learning.
@{fg fill}
   Ask that friend if they are "Slanging" their Words and Sentences. If they
   are, ask them how to say things in a more "Proper/Standard" way. Do not
   ask that friend too much in one day as they might get a bit irretated. An
   example of this is to ask dictionary type questions:@{fg shine}
   Why do you say "So And So" in one sentence and say "So And So" in another
   when both sentences are the same?"@{fg fill}.@{fg shine} "Is that an Adjective or a Verb?"@{fg fill}.
   I fell into this trap. You have to realize that your friend is NOT Your
   Teacher and that they might only speak their language the same way as you
   speak yours (I.e They do not eat Dictionaries for Breakfast either!).@{fg text}

 * Read Newspapers and Kids Books, prefably with a foreign friend around
   to help you, if need be.
@{fg fill}
   Try to avoid reading items such as Foreign Comics, Foreign Newspapers and
   Foreign Magazines that comprise of two languages and are based in your
   own country. For example. If you read a Filipino Newspaper, based in
   England, the articles normally comprise of Tagalog and English. If the
   article writer is not fluent enough in both languages, which is normally
   the case, what tends to happen is the Tagalog gets English-ized. This may
   mean broken English, broken Tagalog, misinterpretation, lack of learning
   (because proper Tagalog words are substituted by incorrect translations),
   etc.@{fg text}

 * Listen to Music/Slow Worded Songs, The Radio/Slow Speaking Presenters,
   etc.

 * Do not Read, Write and/or Translate everything Literally.

 * Try and make a Tape for yourself with a few basic Sentences, etc on it.
   So that you can go Jogging for example and learn your foreign language at
   the same time.

 * Do not keep putting off your learning. When you have nothing to do, or if
   you are bored, or if there is nothing on Television, etc why not switch
   on your Tape, as above, and learn some more.

 * Some days just listen to your foreign friends talking to each other and
   try to translate what they are saying.
@endnode

@node Starting "Getting Started"

@{fg shine} From the Startup-Sequence@{fg text}

 Put LGUI into the C drawer, of the floppy disk or hard drive you are going
 to boot with. To run LGUI simply re-boot your amiga. If you try and boot
 from a floppy drive when you have an hard drive the hard drive will have
 priority over the floppy drive. If you only have floppy drives or only have
 a hard drive then LGUI will boot as normal.

 @{" CLI Arguments " Link "Arguments"}

@{fg shine} From CLI@{fg text}

 Put LGUI anywhere you please. In your C drawer, Tools drawer or where ever.
 Start a CLI Process (I.e use CLI, Shell or Workbench's `Execute' menu) and
 type the pathname for LGUI (I.e DF1:Tools/LGUI, LGUI, etc) and then press
 ENTER. This will run LGUI. Alternatively. Type the pathname for LGUI
 followed by one or more CLI Arguments and then press ENTER.

 @{" CLI Arguments " Link "Arguments"}

@{fg shine} From Workbench@{fg text}

 Make sure there is a TOOL Icon on LGUI and then double-click on LGUI. This
 will run LGUI, which will then read the TOOL Icon for LGUI ToolTypes. If it
 finds any it will set the appropriate values inside LGUI.

 @{" ToolTypes    " Link "ToolTypes"}
@endnode

@node Arguments "CLI Arguments"

@{fg fill} Below is a list of LGUI CLI Keywords with their Arguments. LGUI will not
 interpret an argument if its keyword is missing. I.e You cannot just type
 the argument WORK: without typing the keyword DEVICE_LOADFROM for example
 as other keywords might use a WORK: argument. Thus, LGUI would have an hard
 time differentiating everything.

 You can use more than one keyword/argument set. Example:

 LGUI DEVICE_LOADFROM WORK: WORKBENCH_CLOSE YES

 Keywords and Arguments must be UPPERCASE. As a result of you Typing in
 uppercase LGUI does not get clogged up with conversion code, opening of
 the Utility.Library, etc.

@{fg shine} CLI Arguments@{fg text}

 SPEECH_PRIORITY Number

 The number can be from 0 upto 255. The default is 100. Using an high number
 (past 100) means most programs will get locked out (will not run) whilst
 your speech is being spoken. Whereas a low number (under 100) means Audio
 breaks might occur in your speech.


 DEVICE_LOADFROM DeviceName tells LGUI which device to use, with the drawer
 LanguageGUI, for Loading operations. For example. LGUI DEVICE_LOADFROM DF0:
 tells LGUI that your Language Files should be found in the drawer
 DF0:LanguageGUI.

 DEVICE_SAVETO DeviceName tells LGUI which device to use, with the drawer
 LanguageGUI, for Saving operations. For example. LGUI DEVICE_SAVETO DF0:
 tells LGUI that the Configuration File is to be saved in the drawer
 DF0:LanguageGUI.

 DeviceName can be:

       DH0:  DH1:  DH2:  DH3:  WORK: or LGUI:   Hard Drive Device/Partition.

                     DF0:  DF1:  DF2: or DF3:   Floppy Drives.


 WORKBENCH_CLOSE YES tells LGUI to try and Close (shut down) Workbench. In
 certain cases Workbench might not get closed (usually because another
 program is using Workbench, etc) hence the reason I said "Try and Close".
 Refer to an AmigaDos book or similar for more information on the
 CloseWorkbench() function.

 You can, as mentioned, enter more than one CLI Argument:

 LGUI DEVICE_LOADFROM DF0: DEVICE_SAVETO DF1: WORKBENCH_CLOSE YES

@{fg fill} Default values are used when a CLI Argument is not used/entered. RAM: is
 the default value for DeviceName, although it is not recommended. I only
 use RAM: for small files and for programming purposes. NO is the default
 value for WORKBENCH_CLOSE.@{fg text}
@endnode

