@node Files "Files"

 With regards to the Language side of things, you have two sets of ASCII
 files. One set are known as the Default Files because they contain your
 own, Default, speaking language. For example, if you are English the
 Default Files should be written in the English. The other set of files
 are known as the Foreign Files because they contain the, Foreign, speaking
 language that you are learning. For example, if you are learning French the
 Foreign Files should be written in French.

 The idea of LGUI is to allow you to learn a Foreign Language, with the
 Words and Sentences as defined in the above files, with as much ease as
 possible by giving you a G.U.I that has basic Testing functions, aswell
 as Speech functions. Thus, you could be Reading, Writing and/or Speaking
 Foreign Words/Sentences within a short space of time (depending on your
 learning capabilities, etc).

 LGUI starts by looking for the file `DeviceName:LanguageGUI/LGUI.Config'.
 If it is not found, default configuration values are used.

 Make sure you have the LanguageGUI drawer on your DeviceName.

 The next file LGUI looks for is `DeviceName:LanguageGUI/Titles.Lgui'.
 If it is not found, default titles are used instead.

 The Language files are looked for next. If a language file cannot be found,
 LGUI will tell you the name of that file and then show you the Quit button!

 Once the above files have been successfully loaded LGUI then looks for the
 two, optional, speech files. Namely `DeviceName:LanguageGUI/FNSpeech.Lgui'
 and `DeviceName:LanguageGUI/FSSpeech.Lgui'. If a Speech file cannot be
 found or something is wrong with it (I.e the Format is incorrect), speech
 will not be available for that Catagory. So if something goes wrong with
 the `FNSpeech.Lgui' file, but not with the `FSSpeech.Lgui' file, speech
 will not be available for the Foreign Nouns but will be available for the
 Foreign Sentences.

 The Narrator.Device and Translator.Library are only used when you press the
 SPEAK button in LGUI. Thus, you could have bigger files on DF0: for example
 (because space would not be needed for the Narrator.Device and Translator-
 .Library upon startup) and then use speech later by Assigning the Devs/ and
 Libs/ drawers to another disk.

 @{" File Formats " Link "Formats"}
@endnode

@node Formats "File Formats"
@{fg fill}
 LGUI Files have to be in an ASCII (Text) Format. To see how each LGUI File
 is made simply load up a Text Editor, with a SHOW EOL (Show End Of Line)
 function in it, and then load an LGUI File.@{fg shine}

 Sentence Files@{fg text}

 @0044               <-- The number of Sentences in this Category.
 Sentence (Line 1)   <-- One, Two Lined, Sentence.
 Sentence (Line 2)
 Sentence (Line 1)   <-- Another, Two Lined, Sentence.
 Sentence (Line 2)
 ETC                 <-- Keep building up your Sentences, if need be.
 ETC
 *                   <-- End of the Category, Marker.
 @0025               <-- The next sentence category - Which should be the
 ETC                     same format as the above sentence category.

 You keep doing the above until you have made 22 Categories. After
 inserting a line (regardless if that line contains the Number Of Sentences,
 a Sentence Line or an End Of Category Marker) you must press ENTER/RETURN
 after that line (to give it an EOL code).

 Each Sentence Line must be 43 Characters in length, regardless if that
 Sentence Line is BLANK (42 Spaces and 1 EOL code) or with text in it
 (42 Characters and 1 EOL code). Also, each Sentence File must have 22
 Categories in it - With each category having at least 4 Sentence Lines
 in it, as described above.
@{fg shine}
 Word Files@{fg text}

 @0002                            <-- The number of Words in this Category.
 One Word Line of 42 Characters   <-- One Word Line.
 One Word Line of 42 Characters   <-- One Word Line.
 ETC
 ETC
 *                                <-- End of the Category, Marker.
 @0023                            <-- The next word category - Which should
 ETC                                  be the same format as the above word
 ETC                                  category.
 *

 You keep doing the above until you have made 22 Categories. After inserting
 a line (regardless if that line contains the Number Of Words, a Word Line
 or an End Of Category Marker) you must press ENTER/RETURN after that line
 (to give it an EOL code).

 Each Word Line must be 43 Characters in length, regardless if that
 Word Line is BLANK (42 Spaces and 1 EOL code) or with text in it
 (42 Characters and 1 EOL code). Also, each Word File must have 22
 Categories in it - With each category having at least 4 Word Lines
 in it, as described above.
@{fg shine}
 Titles File@{fg text}

 Word Title One             <-- Word Titles 1 To 22.
 Word Title Two
 ...ETC, ETC...
 ...ETC, ETC...
 Word Title Twenty-Two
 Sentence Title One         <-- Sentence Titles 1 To 22.
 Sentence Title Two
 ...ETC, ETC...
 ...ETC, ETC...
 Sentence Title Twenty-Two

 In this file there are no End Markers, Gaps seperating the Word Titles from
 the Sentence Titles, etc.

 You must have 22 Word Titles and 22 Sentence Titles in your file. The lines
 must be 43 Characters as described above with the Sentence Line.
@{fg shine}
 Speech Files@{fg text}

 @0006          <-- The number of Syllable Lines in your Speech File.
 Heh Lo         <-- A Syllable Line, which can be upto 25 Characters long.
 Good
 Bye
 Morning
 Ee Va Ning
 TOM
 *              <-- End of Syllable Line/s, Marker.
 %0001          <-- The Speaking Word/Sentence to be Activated.
 0001*          <-- The Syllable Line/s to use for Speaking Word/Sentence 1.
 %0004          <-- The Speaking Word/Sentence to be Activated.
 00040006*      <-- The Syllable Line/s to use for Speaking Word/Sentence 4.
 %0009          <-- The Speaking Word/Sentence to be Activated.
 000200030006*  <-- The Syllable Line/s to use for Speaking Word/Sentence 9.

 Press ENTER/RETURN after each line (to give each line an EOL code), as
 described above. The above speech file would have the following output:

 Speaking Word/Sentence 1:  HELLO

 Speaking Word/Sentence 4:  MORNING TOM

 Speaking Word/Sentence 9:  GOOD BYE TOM


 A Speaking Word/Sentence can have upto 25 Syllables Lines Assigned to it,
 provided you have 25 (or more) syllable lines in your speech file of
 course. You can have upto 1500 syllables lines in your speech file. So, if
 you had 1 word per syllable line, you could have 25 words in each Speaking
 Word/Sentence - from a choice of 1500 words.
@{fg fill}
 You can, like I did in the above example, not enter a Speaking
 Word/Sentence into your speech file if you wish. I.e You do not have to
 have speaking words/sentences 1 to 9 in your speech file. You could just
 have speaking words/sentences 1, 4 and 9 only like in my example.

 Each Speaking Word/Sentence must be assigned to valid syllable lines.
 For example. You cannot have six syllable lines and then assign speaking
 word/sentence number one to syllable line 399, thinking that LGUI will use
 a Default Value in this case - LGUI will not and does not use Default
 Values with regards to syllable lines.

 When LGUI comes across a syllable line with Language Text inside it it
 Translates that syllable line's Language Text into Phonetic Text first
 before anything is spoken. You can speed this process up by converting
 your speech files to contain Phonetic Text syllable lines and change any
 % markers into # markers. Read the File_Checker.Guide for more information.
 The # marker tells LGUI that the Speaking Word (or Speaking Sentence) to be
 activated is already in Phonetic Text format. Thus, no need to Translate.
 All phonetic text syllable lines must contain Phonemes - They cannot
 contain both language text and phonetic text.

 The above formats are not Idiot Proof. I cannot make LGUI check your files
 thoroughly without clogging LGUI with Error Requests/ers. Thus, use the
 above formats as above and you should not have any problems?

 * Both Sentence files have to be of the same size. Also, all the Word files
   have to be of the same size as one another.

 * The Word files and the Sentence files are not related - The words found
   in the Sentence files come from the Sentence files and not from any of
   the Word files.

 * LGUI is set up for 1,500 Speaking Words and 1,500 Speaking Sentences.
   If you have more words (or sentences) than this then, of course, you will
   not be able to have a Speaking Word (or Speaking Sentence) for each of
   your words (or sentences).

 * LGUI Speech is meant for your Foreign Language only. The reason why there
   is no Default Language speech is because it is expected you can speak the
   default language or at least know it well enough not to need speech for
   it. I acknowledge there are cases where the default language is your
   second national language, for example, and you may not be too well up on
   it. But LGUI is firstly for the default language to be your own, first,
   national language (your speaking tongue).

 LGUI Speech is meant to be chopped into Syllables for the simple reason
 that LGUI is meant for teaching purposes (I.e The User has a chance to
 understand Each and Every Word/Sentence syllable by syllable as opposed
 to a foreign word/sentence sounding like it is coming at you at 100Mph).
@endnode

@node MScreen "The MAIN Screen"
@{fg shine}
    AUTO  @{fg text} Puts LGUI in Automatic Mode. This means the computer will display
           your Word/s (or Sentence/s) automatically. You simply supply the
           Delay functions and AUTO does the rest.

           @{" The PREFS Window " Link "PWindow"}
@{fg shine}
  MANUAL  @{fg text} Puts LGUI in Manual Mode. This gives you more control over your
           Word/s and Sentence/s simply because you are now in control of
           them. Thus, you decide what should be displayed, what should not
           be displayed, how long to display a Word or Sentence, etc.
@{fg fill}
           When using this function, to get back to Manual Mode from
           Automatic Mode, you only need to press or click the AUTO button
           once and then wait for the current item/s to be displayed before
           Manual Mode comes back into effect.@{fg shine}

 BUTTONS  @{fg text} The Brown/Yellow Off/On Buttons allow you to choose which items
           (Word, Sentence, Pro/Noun, Adjective and Ad/Verb) are to be
           shown. Any items that are Switched OFF (Brown) can be shown later
           with the REVEAL function (Manual Mode) or will be shown after a
           <Delay Rate> (Automatic Mode).

           * Manual Mode only. See REVEAL below.
@{fg shine}
    NEXT  @{fg text} Displays the next Word/s (or next Sentence/s).

           * Manual Mode only.
@{fg shine}
  REVEAL  @{fg text} Reveals any Word/s (or Sentence/s) that were not displayed by the
           NEXT function, above. The normal thing to do is set up LGUI, via
           the Brown/Yellow Toggle Buttons above, so that NEXT displays your
           Default Word/s (or Default Sentence/s) and REVEAL displays your
           Foreign Word/s (or Default Sentence/s).

           * Manual Mode only.
@{fg shine}
   SPEAK  @{fg text} Speaks the current Foreign Word (or Sentence), if the current
           Foreign Word (or Sentence) is Speakable.

           * Manual and Automatic Modes.
@{fg shine}
   PAUSE  @{fg text} Pauses LGUI for <Pause Rate> time. If the <Pause Rate> is Zero
           LGUI will pause until you press the Right-Mouse-Button

           @{" The PREFS Window " Link "PWindow"}
@{fg fill}
           When using this function you only need to press or click the
           PAUSE button once. The <Pause Rate> will come into effect when
           the current item/s have been displayed.@{fg text}

           * Automatic Mode only.
@{fg shine}
    DOWN  @{fg text} The Down-Cursor Key, on the NumericPad, is used to view the
           previous item/s. The two main reasons for this are that you did
           not quite memorize/see an item (perhaps because your <Pause Rate>
           was not slow enough) or that you want to skip through those items
           you have learnt already.@{fg text}

           * Manual Mode only. Speech can be used.
@{fg shine}
      UP  @{fg text} Same as above, but for viewing the next item/s.
