@node PWindow "The PREFS Window"
@{fg shine}
  D/F LINES@{fg text}  This is the Delay, for Sentences only, between Line 1
             (already shown) and Line 2 (to be shown after this Delay).
@{fg shine}
       AUTO@{fg text}  When all the Words (or Sentences) have been shown this Auto
             Delay will be used, before the next Words (or Sentences) are
             shown.
@{fg shine}
   SPELLING@{fg text}  Used with SPELL. This is the Delay between each Character
             appearing.
@{fg shine}
       WORD@{fg text}  Used with WORD-SPLIT. This is the Delay between each Word
             appearing.
@{fg shine}
     REVEAL@{fg text}  This is the Delay that occurs when either the Default item/s
             or the Foreign item/s have been switched off, but not when both
             items are off or on. For example. If you have the Default
             Sentences switched on and the Foreign Sentences switched off
             the Reveal Delay will occur when the Default Sentences have
             been shown. The Foreign Sentences will get shown after the
             Reveal Delay.

             * Works in Automatic Mode only.
@{fg shine}
 PAUSE RATE@{fg text}  The Pause Rate for the PAUSE function on the Main Screen.
@{fg fill}
 If you enter a value of 0 for any of the above delay/pause rates it means
 you do not require a delay/pause.

 You do not have to enter 3 numbers, for example, when you only need to
 enter 2 numbers (I.e you can enter 023 or simply 23). However. As my string
 update routine does not filter out leading zeros, the numbers will appear
 as 023 for example and not as 23. For now, I would stick to using 3 digits
 instead of 2 digits.
@{fg shine}
      VOICE@{fg text}  This selects the current Voice to use. The Voices are defined
             by STM V3. Both the STM and LGUI Configuration files have each
             others Default Configuration values inside them. To make a new
             configuration file that will work with both programs simply do
             the following:

             Define your Voice values with STM V3 and then save the
             configuration file as:  LGUI.Config

             When LGUI has loaded (with the above LGUI.Config file) define
             your Delays etc and then save the configuration file. It will
             be saved as LGUI.Config again. It can now be used with STM V3
             and LGUI, as it has the configuration values of both programs
             inside it.
@{fg shine}
 WORD SPLIT@{fg text}  Tells LGUI that you wish to split each Word line into three
             seperate Words, containing upto 14 Characters in each Word.
@{fg shine}
      SPELL@{fg text}  Tells LGUI that you wish to have every Word (or Sentence)
             spelt. It uses the SPELLING Delay to determine how long each
             character in a Word (or Sentence) is delayed for.
@{fg shine}
     SPEECH@{fg text}  Tells LGUI to switch Off/On speech.
@{fg shine}
     RANDOM@{fg text}  If this is ON it means you wish to learn your Word/s
             (or Sentence/s) RANDOMly, as opposed to IN ORDER.
@{fg shine}
  MISC. ALL@{fg text}  Miscellaneous All, when ON, tells LGUI that you would like the
             last category of a section (which should be named as either
             Miscellaneous Words or Miscellaneous Sentences) to include all
             the other categories of that section. This would allow you to
             learn each sentence, of each category, for example. If you are
             really Brave! use the RANDOM function aswell. MISC. ALL is for
             those people who have learnt about 80%+ of a Language and feel
             the need for a real test!
@endnode

@node SWindow "The SEARCH Window"
@{fg shine}
 I will show you an example of SEARCH rather than try to explain it in
 detail.@{fg text}

 1) Select a Category from the Options Screen and then enter the Search
    Window.@{fg fill}

    The search will be isolated to look in this category only. The idea
    behind this isolation is for quick searching. For example. If the word
    you want to search for is KNIFE why search each category when you know
    that the word KNIFE would, more than likely, be in a `Kitchen' category
    and not in every category.@{fg text}

 2) If the word you are searching for is a WORD, you have the choice of
    selecting Pro/Noun, Adjective or Ad/Verb for the type of word to search
    and Default or Foreign for the type of Language. If the word you are
    searching for is a SENTENCE, you only have the choice of Default or
    Foreign for the type of Language. So, if you were to use the word KNIFE
    as a WORD you could select DEFAULT (because you do not know the Foreign
    equivalent of the word KNIFE) and PRO/NOUN (because you are using a
    Noun). If you were to use the word KNIFE as part of a SENTENCE you
    could select DEFAULT.

 3) Click in the Search String box or press `g' and enter the word KNIFE.
    The search will now search your category (hopefully `In The Kitchen'!)
    for the word KNIFE and display its Foreign equivalent if the word KNIFE
    was found. Thus, the above is how you find the foreign equivalent. If
    you know a Foreign word but not its Default equivalent you would choose
    FOREIGN and PRO/NOUN above for your search and then enter your foreign
    word in the Search String box.

    If a search is successful, press CONTINUE to try and find another valid
    search. If you are searching for a WORD, CONTINUE will try and find
    another WORD with KNIFE inside it. If you are searching for a SENTENCE,
    CONTINUE will try and find another SENTENCE with the word KNIFE inside
    it. Note: This paragraph is generalizing. SEARCH is more flexible than
    this. For example. You do not need to type in an whole word/sentence.
    Just one character, or more, is good enough (depending on what you are
    searching for of course).
@{fg fill}
    You can enter another (New) Search String by clicking inside the search
    string box again (or by pressing `g' again).

    Search is Case Sensitive and will accept characters from 32 to 255. Thus
    allowing for some Foreign characters, depending on your current KeyMap,
    etc.

    Because each Category is made into its own File String it means the
    search function might overlap into another category when it is to search
    from the last line of the current category. This will only happen if the
    search reaches the last line of a category, but normally (unless you are
    searching for `a' only or something) the search will not get to the last
    line. For example. If your last line was HOW MUCH IS THIS and you were
    searching for ZEBRA the search will not get to the last line because the
    last line does not contain the word ZEBRA. However, if you were
    searching for HOW the search would reach the last line and display
    HOW MUCH IS THIS before continuing the search for another HOW word in
    the next category. This is the trade off for having each category made
    into its own file string. Another trade off is that because each file
    string is really a category Search has to be case sensitive - In other
    words, it would be pointless changing a file string into Uppercase
    just so that Search would become Non-Case Sensitive. This would also
    mean displaying words/sentences in Uppercase aswell.
@endnode

