@node Update "Update Information"
@{fg shine}
 * LGUI is now programmed in MC68020 Assembly. This means LGUI V3.00 is
   approximately 50k smaller than LGUI V2.21 (OS3) and about twice as fast.
   If you are using an A600 use LGUI V2.20 (it also works on an A1200 and
   was programmed using `Amiga E'). Note. I have now deleted the `Amiga E'
   source code for LGUI.

 * Speech is no longer pre-programmed. Now you define your Voices via the
   STM V3 program which means the voices come from the LGUI.Config file.
   See `The Prefs Window - VOICE'.

 * The SEARCH function is a bit more flexible than in V2.21 as it now allows
   you to search for either a WORD or a SENTENCE without the need to exit
   the search window. Note. In this version, V3.00, the search function
   might not display any/same message/s as in V2.21 due to lack of time
   for checking/testing the search function thoroughly.

 * When saving a LGUI.config file there is no notification message displayed
   due to lack of time and thought as to wether to flash the screen or put
   up a requester, etc.

 * Voice Values. Below are my voice values for Tagalog and German. Keep the
   default Amiga voice values (Read the `STM.Guide') and then make the
   following changes:

   Tagalog Changes:  Sex         Female
                     Pitch       115
                     Rate        165
                     Frequency   18900
                     Enthusiasm  40
                     A/C Values  2,2,2,2

   My Tagalog voice values are based around the MA word, AH sound.


    German Changes:  Pitch       105
                     Rate        145
                     Frequency   21900
                     Enthusiasm  40
                     A/C Values  2,2,2,2

   My German voice values are based around the WER word, VEER sound.
@{fg fill}
 Once you have found reasonable speech values for a language you should not
 need to change those values. For example. The idea of LGUI Speech is to
 have a clear voice so that you can hear the syllables/words of a language.
 In other words, if an Englishman says "Hello" and a Frenchman says "Hello",
 regardless of Accent, they should both have a clear voice. In the case of
 LGUI German for example I used values that reflected a clear voice, but at
 the same time a voice that could pronounce most of the german words in the
 german files. I based the voice on the german word Wer (Veer). If you use
 the Amiga's natuaral voice Veer does not sound correct. With the german
 voice I chose the sound is a lot better and much clearer. It is usually the
 case that a voice has to be programmed based on one particular sound or
 word. With Tagalog it was the Ah sound.@{fg shine}

 * LGUI has now been sent to America, Australia and around Europe. So far I
   have had positive replies from America, Australia, France and Sweden.
   Check out their P.D Libraries. This is because I could afford the £1, or
   so, postage to Australia for example. But I cannot afford £1, or so, all
   the time (I.e sending to 10 countries could mean me spending upto £10).
   The same goes for P.D Libraries - They cannot afford to write to every
   Author for their latest software. Thus, if you are interested in LGUI,
   please contact me first as I cannot guarantee your country having the
   latest version of the LGUI Disks.

 * To see the Filipino Flag, in its correct colours, on the LGUI icon
   do the following:

   1) Set up your Iprefs enviroment.

      See your Workbench Manual and/or Workbench disk for more details.

   2) Delete the necessary enviroment files (I.e. screenmode.prefs, etc)
      from your Env: drawer (which should of been set up to `Ram:Env/Sys')
      and replace those deleted Ram:Env/Sys enviroment files with the
      LGUI enviroment files.

      Once all the necessary enviroment files have been deleted and replaced
      with the LGUI enviroment files the Workbench should change to an 8
      Coloured Workbench, with the Filipino Flag colours.
@endnode
